      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "No worries, I just got carried away with the goblin analogy. In reality, the escrow agent or title company is the one responsible for holding the earnest money, and they're usually required to follow specific regulations and guidelines to ensure the money is handled correctly.\n\nIf the earnest money is lost or mismanaged, the escrow agent or title company is typically liable for the loss. This is because they're acting as a fiduciary, meaning they're responsible for managing the money on behalf of the buyer and the seller. If they fail to do so, they can be held accountable.\n\nIn most cases, the escrow agent or title company will have a clause in their contract that outlines their responsibilities and liabilities. This clause is usually referred to as a \"fiduciary duty\" clause, and it ensures that the escrow agent or title company is held to a high standard of care when managing the earnest money.\n\nFor example, if the escrow agent or title company fails to deposit the earnest money into the correct account, or if they lose the money due to their own negligence, the buyer or seller may be able to sue them for damages. In this case, the court might order the escrow agent or title company to pay back",
